php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Julius Rosenberg","first_name":"Julius","last_name":"Rosenberg","description":"Julius Rosenberg was an American electrical engineer and member of the Communist Party USA who, with his wife Ethel Rosenberg, was convicted in 1951 of conspiracy to commit espionage on behalf of the Soviet Union, and executed at Sing Sing Prison on June 19, 1953. The case was the most prominent capital prosecution of American Communists in U.S. history and remains one of the defining political trials of the early Cold War.\n\nThe government alleged that Julius Rosenberg had recruited his brother-in-law David Greenglass, a U.S. Army machinist at Los Alamos, to pass technical information about the atomic bomb to Soviet intelligence. Greenglass and his wife Ruth received immunity in exchange for his testimony, in which he claimed his sister Ethel had typed up his notes — testimony Greenglass admitted in 2001 he had fabricated to protect his wife. The trial was presided over by Judge Irving Kaufman, who imposed the death sentence over the recommendation of the prosecution and the FBI. The Supreme Court refused to hear the case after multiple stays and appeals. Pope Pius XII, Albert Einstein, Jean-Paul Sartre, and millions of demonstrators around the world appealed for clemency; President Eisenhower refused.\n\nThey left two young sons, Michael and Robert, who were adopted and raised under the surname Meeropol and have spent their adult lives advocating for their parents posthumous exoneration.","state":"New York","race":"White","gender":"Male","birthdate":"1918-05-12","death_date":"1953-06-19","ideologies":["Communism"],"affiliation":["Communist Party USA"],"in_custody":false,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Sing Sing Prison","institution_city":"Ossining","institution_state":"New York","charges":"Conspiracy to commit espionage on behalf of the Soviet Union (50 U.S.C. § 32 — Espionage Act of 1917)","arrest_date":"1950-07-17","incarceration_date":"1951-04-05","release_date":"1953-06-19","sentence":"Death by electrocution; executed at Sing Sing on June 19, 1953","convicted":"Yes — federal jury verdict, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, March 29, 1951"}]}'

php artisan prisoner:add '{"name":"Ethel Rosenberg","first_name":"Ethel","last_name":"Rosenberg","description":"Ethel Greenglass Rosenberg was an American Communist Party member, wife of Julius Rosenberg, and the only American woman executed for a crime other than murder in the twentieth century. She was put to death at Sing Sing Prison on June 19, 1953, alongside her husband, after their conviction for conspiracy to commit espionage on behalf of the Soviet Union.\n\nThe federal prosecution against Ethel rested almost entirely on the testimony of her brother David Greenglass, who claimed she had typed up notes containing atomic bomb information that her husband then passed to Soviet intelligence. In 2001, Greenglass admitted publicly to journalist Sam Roberts that he had fabricated this testimony in order to protect his own wife, Ruth, who had received immunity from prosecution in exchange for his cooperation. Grand jury transcripts unsealed in 2008 confirmed that Greenglass had originally told prosecutors his sister had nothing to do with the alleged espionage — and that the FBI and the U.S. Attorneys office had pressured him to change his story to secure her conviction.\n\nThe death sentence imposed by Judge Irving Kaufman over the recommendation of the prosecution and the FBI drew worldwide condemnation. Her execution required five separate jolts of electricity. She left two young sons, Michael and Robert Meeropol, who have campaigned for her posthumous exoneration; in 2015 they formally petitioned President Obama for an exoneration, which was not granted.","state":"New York","race":"White","gender":"Female","birthdate":"1915-09-28","death_date":"1953-06-19","ideologies":["Communism"],"affiliation":["Communist Party USA"],"in_custody":false,"released":false,"cases":[{"institution_name":"Sing Sing Prison","institution_city":"Ossining","institution_state":"New York","charges":"Conspiracy to commit espionage on behalf of the Soviet Union (50 U.S.C. § 32 — Espionage Act of 1917)","arrest_date":"1950-08-11","incarceration_date":"1951-04-05","release_date":"1953-06-19","sentence":"Death by electrocution; executed at Sing Sing on June 19, 1953","convicted":"Yes — federal jury verdict, U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, March 29, 1951; conviction widely regarded as a miscarriage of justice in light of David Greenglass 2001 admission that his trial testimony against her was fabricated"}]}'

